<ArticleLayout
  title="A Bedside Table That Fits the Room and Routine"
  description="Choose a bedside table by its height, reach, walkway clearance and the few things needed after the bedroom light goes out."
  category="Bedroom"
  faqs={faqs}
  date="Updated July 2026"
  dateModified="2026-07-19"
  readingTime="9 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/bedroom.webp"
  imageAlt="A calm bedroom with a practical bedside table, lamp and soft bedding"
>
  <p>
    A bedside table can match the bed perfectly and still be wrong at two in the morning. The lamp
    switch is out of reach, a glass sits above shoulder height or the drawer opens across the only
    route to the ensuite.
  </p>
  <p>
    Lie on the bed and list what is genuinely needed after the light goes out. Then measure mattress
    height, the gap beside the bed and the walkway with bedding, doors and drawers in their normal
    positions. Choose the smallest setup that supports that routine.
  </p>

  <h2>Start With the Night-Time Reach</h2>
  <p>
    A lamp, glasses, water and a phone may be the entire list. Another person may need a book,
    tissues, hearing equipment or medication stored exactly as directed. Items used every night
    deserve the surface or first drawer; spare cables, receipts and unread books do not.
  </p>
  <p>
    If clothing or linen is filling the bedside drawers, address that storage problem first. The{" "}
    <a href="/guides/bedroom-wardrobe-organisation-what-to-sort-before-buying-storage/">wardrobe organisation guide</a>{" "}
    and{" "}
    <a href="/guides/under-bed-storage-what-to-measure-before-you-buy/">under-bed storage guide</a>{" "}
    can help move occasional belongings to a more suitable zone.
  </p>

  <h2>Measure From the Mattress Top</h2>
  <p>
    Bed-frame height is less useful than the top of the made mattress. Sit and lie in the usual
    position, then check how far the hand reaches comfortably. A very low table can make a glass or
    lamp switch awkward; a high unit can feel imposing and increase the consequences of a spill.
  </p>
  <p>
    Measure table width as well as the available gap. Leave room to walk, make the bed and reach
    nearby robe or ensuite doors. Open every proposed drawer or cupboard to its full extent. A unit
    that fits while closed may make the room unusable while open.
  </p>

  <h2>Choose the Amount of Storage Deliberately</h2>
  <p>
    A simple side table keeps a compact room visually open but exposes everything on top. One drawer
    can contain glasses, tissues and charging leads. Several deep drawers reduce visible clutter and
    often become a catch-all for items that do not belong beside the bed.
  </p>
  <p>
    Open shelves suit a small rotation of books or devices and need regular clearing. A hinged
    cupboard requires door-swing room. If the real need is folded clothing, compare a correctly
    positioned drawer unit rather than asking a bedside table to do two jobs; see the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/bedroom-drawers-tallboys-and-dressers-what-to-check-before-you-buy/">drawers and dressers guide</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Use Wall-Mounted Options With Care</h2>
  <p>
    A floating shelf can free the floor in a narrow room, but its depth, height and load need the same
    attention as freestanding furniture. Confirm the wall construction, hidden services and the
    fixings specified by the manufacturer. Seek qualified help where the installation or wall is
    uncertain.
  </p>
  <p>
    Renters should obtain approval before drilling or changing lighting. A narrow freestanding table
    may be more flexible, provided it is stable on the actual flooring and does not create a new
    toppling or trip risk.
  </p>

  <h2>Plan Lamps, Charging and Cords Together</h2>
  <p>
    Check the power point before choosing the table. The lamp needs a stable base and enough clear
    space around it; charging leads need a route that does not cross the walkway, catch in a drawer
    or become crushed behind furniture. Our{" "}
    <a href="/guides/bedroom-lighting-and-window-coverings-what-to-compare-before-you-buy/">bedroom lighting and window coverings guide</a>{" "}
    covers lamps and room light in more detail.
  </p>
  <p>
    Use power boards, chargers and extension leads only as their instructions direct. Do not
    overload them, cover them with bedding or continue using damaged cords. Keep drinks away from
    electrical equipment. Fixed electrical work belongs with a licensed electrician.
  </p>
  <p>
    Built-in USB ports and wireless charging add convenience and another component that may date
    before the furniture does. Check compatibility and approvals rather than buying the whole table
    for one charging feature.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep the Top Ready for the Night</h2>
  <p>
    Reserve the surface for the few items reached for in bed. A small tray can stop glasses,
    jewellery and a watch from spreading. Use a stable bottle or glass position away from the edge,
    lamp and devices.
  </p>
  <p>
    Medication should be kept according to its label and professional advice, including any
    temperature or child-access requirements. Do not assume an unlocked bedside drawer is secure.
    Health equipment also needs enough clear space to be used as directed.
  </p>

  <h2>Choose a Finish for Real Use</h2>
  <p>
    Gloss and glass show fingerprints and water marks. Textured rattan or fabric drawers collect dust.
    Painted and timber-look finishes can be marked by oils, skincare and drink rings. Check the care
    instructions and whether the surface can be wiped without damaging it.
  </p>
  <p>
    Test stability on the bedroom floor. Thick carpet can make narrow legs feel unsteady; hard floors
    can allow a light table to slide. Any floor protector should stay flat and dry rather than
    introducing another edge to catch a foot.
  </p>

  <h2>Adapt the Setup to the Room</h2>
  <p>
    Shared bedrooms do not need matching tables. One person may need drawers and charging while the
    other needs only a lamp and book. Guest rooms usually need a clear surface, a working light and
    access to a power point, not drawers filled with household overflow.
  </p>
  <p>
    Children's rooms benefit from stable furniture, fewer loose items and cords kept out of unsafe
    reach. Follow product warnings and anchoring instructions for any furniture with a toppling risk.
    Room layout, age and individual needs matter more than completing a matching suite.
  </p>

  <h2>Test the Bedside Setup Before Buying</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>List the items genuinely used after lights-out.</li>
    <li>Measure from the made mattress and test reach while lying down.</li>
    <li>Protect the walkway and open nearby doors and drawers fully.</li>
    <li>Check lamp stability, power access and the complete cord route.</li>
    <li>Keep water separate from electrical items.</li>
    <li>Match storage volume to the night-time routine, not bedroom overflow.</li>
    <li>Follow installation, load and toppling warnings.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A bedside table does not need to match the bed or fill the available gap. It needs to be the right
    height, keep the path clear and hold a short list of night-time items without becoming a second
    wardrobe. Browse the{" "}
    <a href="/categories/bedroom/">Bedroom</a>{" "}
    category and the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/bedroom-storage-ideas-small-australian-rooms/">small bedroom storage guide</a>{" "}
    for the wider room.
  </p>

